	(2166,2137,'biographical_info','I visited Appledore for the first time in the Spring of 2003 as part of a birding trip. Everything about the island captured my imagination, from the rocky terrain, to the 4am ear-splitting nesting-gull chorus, to the frosty spring mornings in unheated dorms.* The birding group of course made regular visits to the banding station while we were there, and like many of my colleagues I was hooked immediately. I took David\'s legendary Dangle, Tangle and Drudge class that fall and, not satisfied with that, returned a couple of weeks later for a few more days before the banding season ended. \r\n\r\nWhile I have had to miss a season here and there, I\'ve been a regular volunteer ever since. I\'ve met many wonderful people on Appledore and learned a great deal from the dedicated and passionate banding staff. I can\'t wait to get back on the island!\r\n\r\n*Though 15 years has *not* been long enough to get used to wetting down my bed-head in a sink with separate taps for cold (freezing) and hot (scalding).'),
