	(2062,1,'2016-05-06 12:33:33','2016-05-06 12:33:33','<em>Committed to the long-term study of migratory birds during stopover. Through partnerships and collaborations, our study of migration expands beyond the Isles of Shoals and coastal New England.</em>\r\n\r\nThe Appledore Island Migration Station (AIMS) is located on Appledore Island in the Gulf of Maine. Each spring and fall, AIMS staff band birds from dawn to dusk, seven days a week, weather permitting.\r\n\r\nThe primary purpose of AIMS is to contribute to research on the migration and stopover ecology of Nearctic-Neotropical migrants. AIMS also provides hands-on educational opportunities for undergraduate and graduate students in the biological sciences. Since the banding station first opened in 1981????, over 120,000 birds have been banded.\r\n\r\nThe banding operation is led by Dr. Sara Morris, Associate Vice President for Academic Affairs at Canisius College in Buffalo, NY. Dr. Morris and other researchers have published scores of research papers based on data collected on Appledore and other banding stations.\r\n\r\nThe AIMS banding station is staffed entirely by volunteers and students.\r\n<h2>History</h2>\r\nThe bird banding station was opened in 1974 by a birding \"hobbyist\", Betty Phinney, who is now deceased.  David Holmes starting banding on the island the following year and, with the exception of 2 years in the late 1970\'s, he has returned to the island every season since then.\r\n\r\n<h3>Notable Captures</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n\r\n<li>A Northern Waterthrush originally banded at Appledore on was trapped and released near Caracas, Venuzuela DATES?</li>\r\n \r\n	<li>A Blackpoll Warbler banded in Newfoundland in 1998 was re-trapped at Appledore on May 20, 1999</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>A Black-and-white Warbler was banded on May 24, 1999 in New Bern, NC, and re-trapped at Appledore on 5/31/1999</li>\r\n\r\n \r\n	<li>A Blue-headed Vireo banded on May 9, 2005 near Knott\'s Island, NC, was re-trapped at Appledore on May 17, 2005</li>\r\n\r\n \r\n	<li>A Common Yellowthroat banded at Manoment, MA on 5/16/2005 was re-trapped at Appledore on 5/18/2005</li>\r\n\r\n \r\n	<li>A Magnolia Warbler originally banded in Fort Morgan, AL on 10/19/2000 was re-captured at Appledore on 9/19/2004</li>','About AIMS','','inherit','closed','closed','','1786-revision-v1','','','2016-05-06 12:33:33','2016-05-06 12:33:33','',1786,'http://burtonux.com/aims/2016/05/06/1786-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
